    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is OpenClaw Memory Stack?</summary>
        <p>A drop-in <strong>OpenClaw</strong> plugin that replaces built-in memory. 5 search engines with rank fusion, a knowledge graph with PageRank, and 3-tier token control (L0 ~100 tokens, L1 ~800, L2 full). Your agent recalls more while using 90% fewer tokens. Runs fully offline — no setup, no API key, no cloud.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How does it improve OpenClaw's memory?</summary>
        <p>5 engines fire in parallel with automatic fallback. Results merge via Reciprocal Rank Fusion + MMR diversity reranking. Decisions and relationships live in a SQLite-backed knowledge graph with multi-hop traversal. Tiered output (L0/L1/L2) controls exactly how many tokens each recall costs. Add your own LLM key (OpenAI, Anthropic, Ollama, MLX, or any compatible provider) and every conversation gets structured fact extraction — the complete Memory Stack experience.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Does it work with OpenClaw's Telegram integration?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Memory Stack plugs into OpenClaw as a native memory provider. It works with Telegram, CLI, and any other OpenClaw channel. No extra configuration needed — install, restart, done.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Does it need an internet connection?</summary>
        <p>All 5 engines, rank fusion, 4-level dedup, and the knowledge graph run locally. No data leaves your machine. For the complete experience, add your own LLM key — supports OpenAI, Anthropic, Ollama, MLX, and any OpenAI-compatible endpoint. Memory Stack auto-detects your provider at startup. Without a key, core search and graph still work fully offline.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How does it save money on API costs?</summary>
        <p>Every token your AI reads costs money. Memory Stack cuts that three ways: (1) Tiered output — auto-recall uses L0 at ~100 tokens, tool searches use L1 at ~800 tokens, full text only loads on demand. Up to 90% fewer tokens per search. (2) It removes duplicate results so you don't pay for the same information twice. (3) Lossless DAG summarization compresses memory hierarchically — your agent drills down only when it needs detail.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is compaction rescue?</summary>
        <p>When OpenClaw conversations get long, the system compresses old messages to fit the context window. Important decisions can get lost in this process. Memory Stack's rescue engine stores key facts (decisions, deadlines, architecture choices) in a dedicated database before compression happens, and retrieves them instantly when relevant — zero wasted tokens re-explaining things.</p>
      </details>
